# gitleaks finding fingerprints: <commit-sha>:<path>:<rule-id>:<line>
#
# Each entry suppresses ONE finding in ONE historical commit. Entries are commit-pinned,
# so a new occurrence of the same string in any new commit still fails the gate. This is
# deliberately not a pattern allowlist: an allowlist broad enough to pass test fixtures
# would be broad enough to pass a real leak, and CLAUDE.md makes secret hygiene
# non-negotiable.
#
# CI runs `gitleaks git --log-opts=--all`, which scans every commit on every branch. A
# planted leak-test secret therefore fails the quality gate on unrelated PRs, and renaming
# it in a later commit does not help — the original commit stays reachable.
#
# Every entry below is the same M1-301 leak-test fixture, `sk-live-planted-9d2f1a`,
# flagged as generic-api-key because `sk-live-` is a realistic key prefix and its entropy
# is 3.879. It was never a credential. M1-301 renamed it to the low-entropy form
# `privateFAKE123456`, which the scanner correctly ignores.
#
# This list was written when only the first two commits existed and said it was closed.
# That was wrong: M1-301's review rounds 2 and 3 landed *before* the rename, and each added
# new occurrences of the old value in new commits. Commit-pinning is working exactly as
# designed here — every new commit carrying the string failed the gate and had to be listed
# deliberately. The list is closed as of the rename in 0ee2199; anything after that commit
# containing this value is a real finding, not a known one.
#
# Lesson for future leak tests, and the reason there are five entries instead of zero:
# a planted secret must be distinctive in program output, not realistic-looking. Use the
# FAKE-infix low-entropy form from the first commit that plants it. Renaming later does not
# retire the finding, because the original commits stay reachable forever.

